## [[Unsorted/History of Geology\|History of Geology]]

<div class="transclusion internal-embed is-loaded"><div class="markdown-embed">







## History
- Greek philosophers
	- First records
	- [[Unsorted/Aristotle\|Aristotle]]
		- "Geological change is too slow to be observed in one person's lifetime"
	- Theopratus, on stones
		- Noted colors of minerals once they're heated
- Roman philosophers
	- Pliny the Elder
		- Invented the encyclopedia
		- Detect counterfeit gemstones by trying to scratch them
- Middle-late Europe
	- James Ussher
		- Father of Catastrophism
			- Believed all major geologic features were formed from single catastrophic events
			- Biblical flood, etc
	- James Hutton
		- Uniformitarianism
			- Noticed a strange rock formation at Siccar point
				- ![Pasted image 20221103131602.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
				- Bottom stratum of greywacke, vertically-aligned
				- Top stratum of red sandstone, horizontally-aligned
				- Revealed notion that rocks form horizontal, and different [[strata\|strata]] form at very different times
			- Most geologic processes happen over extreme lengths of time
	- Charles Lyell
		- Defined Uniformitarianism
			- The physical, chemical, biological, and geologic laws thatoperate today have operated throughout the geologic past
		- Modified into Actualism
			- Geology can be explained through actual processes that occur today
			- The present is the key to the past
				- Idea that forces that act today were at work in the past
			- Some processes are not directly observable, but are evident due to extensive research
		- Charles Darwin
			- Actualism also influenced Darwin's theories about evolution
				- Slow changes over vast timescales

</div></div>



## Types
-   **Physical geology** seeks to understand the earth's processes, as they are today
-   **Historical geology** seeks to understand the origin and history of the[[Unsorted/Earth\|Earth]]

## Geologic time

^755f91

- About 90% of geologic time happened during the precambrian
	- Very few fossils, none complex
- Absolutely gargantuan compared to human timescales
